\description{
An \strong{unreferenced species} is a described taxon that has \strong{no barcode sequence}
for the target marker in any reference database.  Because TaxaMatch can
only return taxa that have reference sequences, an unreferenced species can never
appear as a named match candidate -- even if it is the true source of the
observed sequence.  Adding unreferenced species as explicit hypotheses allows the
LLM (via \code{\link[TaxaAssign:assign_taxa_llm]{TaxaAssign::assign_taxa_llm()}}) to evaluate their geographic
plausibility alongside the named match candidates.
}
\details{
\strong{Example:} a 12S eDNA read from \emph{Fundulus parvipinnis} (no reference
sequence) matches most closely to \emph{Fundulus lima} (has reference).
Without unreferenced species insertion, \emph{F. parvipinnis} can never be the top hypothesis.
With unreferenced species insertion, the LLM recognises that \emph{F. parvipinnis} is the
native Southern California congener and ranks it above \emph{F. lima}.
\subsection{Unreferenced species definition}{

For each genus represented in \code{match_df}, the function:
\enumerate{
\item Retrieves all described species in the genus (from NCBI taxonomy,
or from a user-supplied \code{species_list}).
\item Removes species already in \code{match_df} -- these have reference
sequences by definition and are skipped (skip-list optimisation).
\item For each remaining species, queries NCBI nucleotide with
\code{retmax = 0} (count only) to check whether a barcode sequence exists.
\item Species with \strong{count = 0} are unreferenced.
\item Species with \strong{count > 0} but absent from \code{match_df} represent a
reference completeness gap (reported separately in the census).
}
}

\subsection{Species list completeness}{

NCBI taxonomy is the default species source but is not exhaustive: some
described species appear only in GBIF, FishBase, WoRMS, or other
authorities.  Species absent from the chosen source are also unreferenced but
will be missed.  Supply a more complete list via \code{species_list} when
taxonomic completeness is critical (e.g. well-studied vertebrate genera).
}

